/*****************************************************************
 * File:    Compiler.doc
 * Purpose: Describe the compiler
 * Author:  Karl Abrahamson
 ****************************************************************/


           =============================================
           High level description of Astarte translator.
           =============================================

  REMARKS
  Terminology in the code is somewhat strange, since some of the code
  was written before the terminology was modified.  
  The word 'type' is sometimes used to mean a species.
  The word 'class' is sometimes used to mean genus, community, 
  species or family.  The word 'entity' is used for a data item.
  The word 'place' is used for shared box, and 'box' for nonshared box.



     =====================================================
    			Anatomy
     =====================================================

The main program is in src/parser/compiler.c.  It processes command line
arguments, initializes, and starts the parser.

The parser is in src/parser/parser.y.  It reads the input through a 
lexer that has three stages: preprocessing to handle imports; the
main lexer (src/lexer/lexer.lex) and postprocessing that handles
such things as pushbacks.  The parser forms data structures (parse trees)
and passes them to a declaration handler.

Declaration handlers are in directory src/dcls. Some declarations, such 
as abbreviations and assumptions, are handled immediately by placing entries
in tables.  Declarations that require type inference are handled by
file src/dcls/dcl.c.  Simple declarations are typically handled by making
table entries.  

For declarations such as define-declarations, processing is done in 
the following order.

  (1) Identifiers are handled (src/ids/ids.c). Identifiers are
      classified as local or global.  The parser creates a separate node
      for each occurrence of an identifier; the identifier handler
      replaces them by a single shared node.
      Open if, try, etc. constructs are handled (src/ids/open.c).
      Overloaded global identifiers are tagged as such.

  (2) Main type inference is done (src/infer/infer.c).  That includes
      type inference that can be done without knowing types of 
      overloaded identifiers.

  (3) Overloaded identifiers are handled (src/infer/defer.c).  All 
      possibilities are tried.  There are two passes.  The first just
      determines all possibilities, and checks whether any of them 
      contribute to expectations.  The second pass makes table entries and
      generates code.  Stage (4) below is done only on the second pass, and
      stage (5) is done on both passes.  Stages 6 and beyond are only done
      on the second pass.

  (4) Roles are checked (src/error/newrole.c).

  (5) Pattern match substitution is done, and type inference that results
      from choice of translation rule are done (src/patmatch/translt.c).

  (6) Scopes are assigned to local ids and to expressions that require
      autonomous environments (await, function, lazy-list, define 
      expressions). (src/ids/lateids.c)

  (7) The declaration is issued.  Declaration processors are in
      src/dcls/defdcls.c and src/dcls/somedcls.c.

  (8) Code is generated (src/generate/genexec.c).  During code generation, 
     defaults are handled (src/infer/defaults.c).

If an error occurs during type inference, the most promising collection
of bindings is returned to, and an error is reported there.

A declaration processor makes entries in the tables.  The table manager is
in src/tables and src/clstbl.  For declarations that require code 
to be generated, the declaration processor calls the code generator 
in src/generate/genexec.c.
The code generator passes the byte-code through a primitive peephole
optimizer in src/generate/improve.c, which gets rid of some of the 
silly things that the main code generator does.


     ======================================================
     Directories and files for the compiler are as follows.
     ======================================================

***************************************************************************
                            ARCHITECTURE AND CONFIGURATION
***************************************************************************

src/misc/config.h
src/misc/files.h
----------------
  Local configuration.  Where are the directories?  config.h needs
  to be edited to configure.

src/misc/options.h
-------------------
  Top level option selector.  This file needs to be edited to 
  configure the architecture.

src/misc/debug.h
src/misc/prod.h
src/misc/tstconfig.h
----------------
  Compilation options.

src/misc/16bitn.h
src/misc/32bita.h
src/misc/32bitn.h
src/misc/32bita.h
-----------------
  Definitions according to word size and alignment requirements.

src/misc/unixl.h
src/misc/unixm.h
src/misc/unixs.h
src/misc/win16.h
----------------
  Operating system characteristics and more compilation options.

***************************************************************************
                            CONSTANTS, CONTROL
***************************************************************************

src/misc/complain.h
-------------------
  Options for controlling how the compiler complains about bad things.

src/misc/limits.h
-----------------
  Compiled in limits that cannot be exceeded.

src/misc/misc.h
---------------
  Included by every program.  Reads the misc header files, as well as
  stdio.h.  Defines TRUE, FALSE.

src/misc/perform.h
----------------
  Sizes of data structures and parameters that only affect performance.

src/misc/types.h
----------------
  Types used in both the compiler and the interpreter.


***************************************************************************
                            UTILITIES
***************************************************************************

src/utils/filename.c
src/utils/filename.h
--------------------
  Utilities for managing file and directory names.

src/utils/hash*
-------------------
  These files implement hash tables, and are used mainly by the table manager.

  hash.doc: Description
  hash.h:   Prototypes
  hash.c:   General functions
  hash1.c:  Hash tables with just a key
  hash2.c:  Hash tables with a key and a value.

src/utils/lists*
--------------------
  These files implement linked lists.

  lists.doc: 	Description
  lists.h: 	Prototypes
  lists.c: 	Implementation
  listutil.c: 	Assorted utilities for lists, including
		reverse, append, membership testing, delete, copy,
		subscript, length, merge sorted lists, sort,
		intersection, 

src/utils/strops.c
src/utils/t_strops.c
src/utils/strops.h
------------------------
  These files implement misc string and character operations for
  the compiler and the interpreter.
	
src/utils/rdwrt.c
src/utils/rdwrt.h
-------------------------
  Input and output functions used for writing integers into files and
  reading them back, and for placing and getting integers in byte
  arrays.  Used during byte-code generation.

src/alloc/*
-----------
  Storage allocation and freeing.

  allocate.h: Prototypes for all files in directory alloc.
  allocate.c: Basic (generic) storage allocation.
  allocors.c: Allocators and freers for assorted types.
  alocexpr.c: Allocators and freers for exprs (translator structures).
  aloclist.c: Allocators and freers for lists.
  alocrole.c: Allocators and freers for roles.
  aloctype.c: Allocators and freers for types.
  tempstr.c:  Allocation of temporary arrays of bytes.  

***************************************************************************
			DATA STRUCTURES                            
***************************************************************************

src/classes/*
-------------
  These files handle Astarte types, classes, etc. as data structures,
  and also handle roles as data structures.

  type.doc:    Description of type data structure.
  classes.h:   Prototypes for all files in directory classes.
  bring.c:     Processing types for brings.
  type.c:      Build type nodes.
  role.c:      Build role nodes, and role operations
  copytype.c:  Copying type structures.
  printty.c:   Print a type.
  typeutil.c:  Misc utilities for types, including
	       test for hermit type, powers of types, equality test,
	       test for a variable in a class structure, reduction in
	       size, replacement of vars, membership tests in lists.
  t_tyutil.c:  Utilities used by translator, including
	       test for hidden types, setting node fields, 
	       finding a class that contains another, support
	       for run-time variables.


src/exprs/*
------------
  These files handle expressions as a data structure, build expressions
  and examine/modify them.

  expr.doc:     Description of expr data structure.
  expr.h:       Prototypes for all files in directory exprs except prtexpr.c
		and brngexpr.c.  (Why?  Who knows.)
  expr.c:       Build expr nodes.
  brngexpr.h:   Prototypes for brngexpr.c.
  brngexpr.c:   Building expressions for bring declarations.
  choose.c:     Building expressions for building conditionals.
  context.c:    Building expressions for context expressions.
  copyexpr.c:   Copy an expr.
  exprutil.c:   Misc functions for exprs, including
	        general scan_expr, application with NULL treated as (),
	        converting a list to a product expression, test for hermit,
	        skip_sames, inserting one expr at the end of another,
	        setting fields, searching for certain ids, size of an expr,
	        some dynamic storage management support, 
	        marking pattern functions with PAT_FUN,
  prtexpr.h: 	Prototypes for prtexpr.c
  prtexpr.c: 	Print exprs.


***************************************************************************
			TABLE MANAGER                            
***************************************************************************

src/tables/*
------------
  Table manager.

  tables.h:	  Prototypes.
  assume.c:	  Assume tables.
  contrib.c:	  Determinations about what should be put into global
		  id table.
  descrip.c:	  Description table, and managing descriptions.
  fileinfo.c:	  Management of tables that are associated with files.
		  (Here, the structures that keep track of the tables
		  themselves are managed.  The individual tables, once
		  found by this module, are managed by other modules.)
  globtbl.c:      Table of global identifiers.  Here, we remember
		  definitions and expectations.
  idtbl.c:	  Top level interface for globtbl.c and loctbl.c.
  loctbl.c:       Tables for local identifiers and local scopes.
  missing.c:	  Tables of things declared missing.
  primtbl.c:	  Functions for declaring primitives.
  secimp.c:	  Managing second and subsequent imports of packages.
  strtbl.c:	  String table.  (Only one copy of each string is stored.)
  t_compl.c:	  Exhaustiveness tester for definitions.  
  tableman.c:	  Other tables. (Context tables, advisory tables, ...)
  visible.c:	  Management of visibility of definitions that are stored
		  in globtbl.c.

src/clstbl*
-----------
  Tables for managing information about types, data abstractions, etc.

  abbrev.c:	  Abbreviations
  abbrev.h:	  Prototypes.
  classinf.c:	  Information about classes.
  classtbl.c:	  Main table for maintaining information about the species
		  and the abstraction hierarchy.
  classtbl.h:	  Prototypes, etc.
  cnstrlist.c:	  Keeping track of the lists of constructors for species.
  cnstrlist.h:	  Prototypes.
  dflttbl.c:	  Keeping track of defaults for abstractions.
  dflttbl.h:	  Prototypes.
  meettbl.c: 	  Table of meets for abstractions.
  meettbl.h:	  Prototypes.
  stdtytbl.c:	  Functions for creating standard species and abstractions.
  stdtytbl.h:	  Prototypes.
  vartbl.c:	  Table of variable names.
  vartbl.h:	  Prototypes.

***************************************************************************
			LEXER AND PARSER                            
***************************************************************************

src/lexer/*
-----------
  Lexical Analyzer.  The input characters enter the front end of the lexer,
  pass through the core, and come out through a back end.

  lexical.h:	Prototypes for most files in lexer.  
  modes.h:      Definitions of modes.
  modes.c:	Handling of modes.
  lexer.lex:	Lexer core.
  lexerr.c:	Check for error conditions, and maintain shadow of
		parser stack for that purpose.
  preflex.c:    Initialization, front end and back end for lexer.
  lexids.c:	Handling of identifiers for lexer.
  lexsup.c: 	Misc functions for lexer.
  lexvars.c:	Global variables for lexer.


src/parser/*
------------

  The parser.  Here, a stream of tokens from the lexer is broken into 
  declarations, and declarations are processed by calling the appropriate 
  declaration processor.  Expressions and types are converted to data 
  structures.

  parser.h:	Prototypes.
  parser.y:	Parser core.
  asd.c:	Handling of descriptions for asthelp.
  asd.h:	Prototypes.
  compiler.c:	Main program for compiler.  Initialization is done here.
  parseerr.c:	Error checking for parser.
  parsutil.c:	Utility functions for the parser.
  parsvars.c:	Global variables for the parser.
  panic.c:      Handling of panic mode error recovery.
  tokens.h:	Token codes.
  tokmod.h:     Offsets for storing tokens, and extra tokens not used
		in the parser.


***************************************************************************
			IDENTIFIER HANDLING
***************************************************************************

src/ids/*
-----------------
  Handling of identifiers and scoping.

  ids.h: 	Prototypes.
  ids.c: 	Identifier handling.
  lateids.c:	More identifier handling (later in compilation process).
  open.h:	Prototypes for open.c.
  open.c:	Handling of open if, try exprs, etc.

***************************************************************************
			TYPE INFERENCE AND UNIFICATION
***************************************************************************

src/unify/*
-----------
  Unification and related functions for types.

  complete.c:	Determining whether the union of a set of polymorphic
		types completely covers a given polymorphic type.
  constraint.c: Handling of constraints on polymorphic types.
  constraint.h: Prototypes
  overlap.c:	Handling of overlap calculations for polymorphic types.
  unify.h:	Prototypes
  unify.doc:	Discussion of unification.
  unify.c:	Unification of polymorphic types.

src/infer/*
-----------
  Type inference. Part of the declaration handling that is really the
  responsibility of dcls/dcl.c is done in defer.c, because simulating
  backtracking in C forces it.

  infer.h:	Prototypes
  infer.c:	Main type inference
  defer.c:	Handle deferred unifications due to overloaded identifiers.
  defaults.c:	Handle defaults for type and family variables.
  t_unify.c:    Unification of an expr type, with possible deferral for
		overloaded exprs.


***************************************************************************
			PATTERN MATCHING AND EXPANSION                         
***************************************************************************

src/patmatch/*
------------------
  Pattern matching.  These translations are done near the end of
  type inference.

  patmatch.h:		Prototypes
  translt.c:		Pattern match translation
  substit.c:		Perform substitution.
  mode.c:		Compatibility checking
  patutils.c:		Utility functions
  pmcompl.c:		Exhaustiveness checking for choose-matching expressions

***************************************************************************
			DOING DECLARATIONS                            
***************************************************************************

src/dcls/*
----------
  Handling of declarations.  Here, the semantics of declarations is
  processed.

  dcls.h:	Prototypes.
  dcl.c:	Define, let, patternfun, execute, team, description dcl
		handling, top level. (manage id handling, type inference.)
  dclclass.c:   Do species, family, genus and community dcls.  Also
		handle class dcls.
  dclcnstr.c:   Declare automatic functions for species and families.
  dclutil.c:	General functions to support declarations.
  defdcls.c:    Do define and let dcls.
  deferdcl.c:	Handling of declarations that are given during extensions
		that can only be processed at the end of the extension.
  expnddcl.c:	Handling of expand declarations and pattern declarations.
  report.c:	Manages reports of what has been declared, for putting into
		the compiler listing.
  somedcls.c:	Miscellaneous declarations.


***************************************************************************
			CODE GENERATION                            
***************************************************************************

src/generate/*
--------------
  Code generation

  generate.h:	Prototypes.
  generate.c:	Misc functions.
  gendcl.c:	Generate miscellaneous declarations.
  genexec.c:    Code generator for expressions.
  genglob.c: 	Handle generation of global ids.
  genstd.c:	Declare the standard functions, when doing the standard 
		package.
  gentype.c:	Generate code for type expressions.
  improve.c:    Code improver -- back end of code generator.
  prim.c:	Generate primitives.
  prim.h:	Prototypes.
  selmod.c:	Handling of role selectors and modifiers.
  selmod.h:	Prototypes


***************************************************************************
			ERROR REPORTING
***************************************************************************

src/error/*
------------
  Error reporting and checking.

  error.h:	Prototypes
  error.c:	Error reporting.
  newrole.c:	Handling of roles.


***************************************************************************
			MISCELLANEOUS                            
***************************************************************************

src/standard/*
--------------
  Declare standard objects, types, etc.

  stdfuns.h:	Prototypes.
  stdfuns.c: 	Define standard functions, objects.
  stdids.c:	Names of standard functions, types, etc.
  stdids.h:	Internal names for standard ids.
  stdtypes.h:	Prototypes.
  stdtypes.c:	Define standard species, families, abstractions.

src/debug/*
-----------
  Support for debugging the compiler.

disassemble.c
--------------
  This is a disassembler that can be used to read the byte code that
  the compiler produces.  Write

    disass pack.aso

  to print a symbolic form of pack.aso on the standard output.

  






    
